#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.13.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "This release supports Python 2.7 and 3.4 - 3.6."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:9
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:11
msgid ""
"Operations like ``a + b + c`` will reuse temporaries on some platforms, "
"resulting in less memory use and faster execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:13
msgid ""
"Inplace operations check if inputs overlap outputs and create temporaries to "
"avoid problems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:15
msgid ""
"New ``__array_ufunc__`` attribute provides improved ability for classes to "
"override default ufunc behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:17 ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:28
msgid "New ``np.block`` function for creating blocked arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:21
msgid "New functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:23
msgid "New ``np.positive`` ufunc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:24
msgid "New ``np.divmod`` ufunc provides more efficient divmod."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:25
msgid "New ``np.isnat`` ufunc tests for NaT special values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:26
msgid "New ``np.heaviside`` ufunc computes the Heaviside function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:27
msgid "New ``np.isin`` function, improves on ``in1d``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:29
msgid "New ``PyArray_MapIterArrayCopyIfOverlap`` added to NumPy C-API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:31
msgid "See below for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:35
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:37
msgid ""
"Calling ``np.fix``, ``np.isposinf``, and ``np.isneginf`` with ``f(x, "
"y=out)`` is deprecated - the argument should be passed as ``f(x, out=out)``, "
"which matches other ufunc-like interfaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:40
msgid ""
"Use of the C-API ``NPY_CHAR`` type number deprecated since version 1.7 will "
"now raise deprecation warnings at runtime. Extensions built with older f2py "
"versions need to be recompiled to remove the warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:43
msgid ""
"``np.ma.argsort``, ``np.ma.minimum.reduce``, and ``np.ma.maximum.reduce`` "
"should be called with an explicit `axis` argument when applied to arrays "
"with more than 2 dimensions, as the default value of this argument "
"(``None``) is inconsistent with the rest of numpy (``-1``, ``0``, and ``0``, "
"respectively)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:47
msgid ""
"``np.ma.MaskedArray.mini`` is deprecated, as it almost duplicates the "
"functionality of ``np.MaskedArray.min``. Exactly equivalent behaviour can be "
"obtained with ``np.ma.minimum.reduce``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:50
msgid ""
"The single-argument form of ``np.ma.minimum`` and ``np.ma.maximum`` is "
"deprecated. ``np.maximum``. ``np.ma.minimum(x)`` should now be spelt ``np.ma."
"minimum.reduce(x)``, which is consistent with how this would be done with "
"``np.minimum``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:54
msgid ""
"Calling ``ndarray.conjugate`` on non-numeric dtypes is deprecated (it should "
"match the behavior of ``np.conjugate``, which throws an error)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:56
msgid ""
"Calling ``expand_dims`` when the ``axis`` keyword does not satisfy ``-a.ndim "
"- 1 <= axis <= a.ndim``, where ``a`` is the array being reshaped, is "
"deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:62
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:64
msgid ""
"Assignment between structured arrays with different field names will change "
"in NumPy 1.14. Previously, fields in the dst would be set to the value of "
"the identically-named field in the src. In numpy 1.14 fields will instead be "
"assigned 'by position': The n-th field of the dst will be set to the n-th "
"field of the src array. Note that the ``FutureWarning`` raised in NumPy 1.12 "
"incorrectly reported this change as scheduled for NumPy 1.13 rather than "
"NumPy 1.14."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:74
msgid "Build System Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:76
msgid ""
"``numpy.distutils`` now automatically determines C-file dependencies with "
"GCC compatible compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:81
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:84
msgid "Error type changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:86
msgid ""
"``numpy.hstack()`` now throws ``ValueError`` instead of ``IndexError`` when "
"input is empty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:88
msgid ""
"Functions taking an axis argument, when that argument is out of range, now "
"throw ``np.AxisError`` instead of a mixture of ``IndexError`` and "
"``ValueError``. For backwards compatibility, ``AxisError`` subclasses both "
"of these."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:94
msgid "Tuple object dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:96
msgid ""
"Support has been removed for certain obscure dtypes that were "
"unintentionally allowed, of the form ``(old_dtype, new_dtype)``, where "
"either of the dtypes is or contains the ``object`` dtype. As an exception, "
"dtypes of the form ``(object, [('name', object)])`` are still supported due "
"to evidence of existing use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:103
msgid "DeprecationWarning to error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:104 ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:117
msgid "See Changes section for more detail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:106
msgid "``partition``, TypeError when non-integer partition index is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:107
msgid ""
"``NpyIter_AdvancedNew``, ValueError when ``oa_ndim == 0`` and ``op_axes`` is "
"NULL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:108
msgid "``negative(bool_)``, TypeError when negative applied to booleans."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:109
msgid ""
"``subtract(bool_, bool_)``, TypeError when subtracting boolean from boolean."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:110
msgid ""
"``np.equal, np.not_equal``, object identity doesn't override failed "
"comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:111
msgid ""
"``np.equal, np.not_equal``, object identity doesn't override non-boolean "
"comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:112
msgid ""
"Deprecated boolean indexing behavior dropped. See Changes below for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:113
msgid "Deprecated ``np.alterdot()`` and ``np.restoredot()`` removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:116
msgid "FutureWarning to changed behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:119
msgid "``numpy.average`` preserves subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:120
msgid "``array == None`` and ``array != None`` do element-wise comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:121
msgid ""
"``np.equal, np.not_equal``, object identity doesn't override comparison "
"result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:124
msgid "dtypes are now always true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:126
msgid ""
"Previously ``bool(dtype)`` would fall back to the default python "
"implementation, which checked if ``len(dtype) > 0``. Since ``dtype`` objects "
"implement ``__len__`` as the number of record fields, ``bool`` of scalar "
"dtypes would evaluate to ``False``, which was unintuitive. Now ``bool(dtype) "
"== True`` for all dtypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:133
msgid ""
"``__getslice__`` and ``__setslice__`` are no longer needed in ``ndarray`` "
"subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:134
msgid ""
"When subclassing np.ndarray in Python 2.7, it is no longer _necessary_ to "
"implement ``__*slice__`` on the derived class, as ``__*item__`` will "
"intercept these calls correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:138
msgid ""
"Any code that did implement these will work exactly as before. Code that "
"invokes ``ndarray.__getslice__`` (e.g. through ``super(...).__getslice__``) "
"will now issue a DeprecationWarning - ``.__getitem__(slice(start, end))`` "
"should be used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:144
msgid ""
"Indexing MaskedArrays/Constants with ``...`` (ellipsis) now returns "
"MaskedArray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:145
msgid ""
"This behavior mirrors that of np.ndarray, and accounts for nested arrays in "
"MaskedArrays of object dtype, and ellipsis combined with other forms of "
"indexing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:150
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:153
msgid "GUfuncs on empty arrays and NpyIter axis removal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:154
msgid ""
"It is now allowed to remove a zero-sized axis from NpyIter. Which may mean "
"that code removing axes from NpyIter has to add an additional check when "
"accessing the removed dimensions later on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"The largest followup change is that gufuncs are now allowed to have zero-"
"sized inner dimensions. This means that a gufunc now has to anticipate an "
"empty inner dimension, while this was never possible and an error raised "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:162
msgid ""
"For most gufuncs no change should be necessary. However, it is now possible "
"for gufuncs with a signature such as ``(..., N, M) -> (..., M)`` to return a "
"valid result if ``N=0`` without further wrapping code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:167
msgid "``PyArray_MapIterArrayCopyIfOverlap`` added to NumPy C-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:168
msgid ""
"Similar to ``PyArray_MapIterArray`` but with an additional "
"``copy_if_overlap`` argument. If ``copy_if_overlap != 0``,  checks if input "
"has memory overlap with any of the other arrays and make copies as "
"appropriate to avoid problems if the input is modified during the iteration. "
"See the documentation for more complete documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:176
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:179
msgid "``__array_ufunc__`` added"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:180
msgid ""
"This is the renamed and redesigned ``__numpy_ufunc__``. Any class, ndarray "
"subclass or not, can define this method or set it to ``None`` in order to "
"override the behavior of NumPy's ufuncs. This works quite similarly to "
"Python's ``__mul__`` and other binary operation routines. See the "
"documentation for a more detailed description of the implementation and "
"behavior of this new option. The API is provisional, we do not yet guarantee "
"backward compatibility as modifications may be made pending feedback. See "
"`NEP 13`_  and documentation_ for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:193
msgid "New ``positive`` ufunc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:194
msgid ""
"This ufunc corresponds to unary `+`, but unlike `+` on an ndarray it will "
"raise an error if array values do not support numeric operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:198
msgid "New ``divmod`` ufunc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:199
msgid ""
"This ufunc corresponds to the Python builtin `divmod`, and is used to "
"implement `divmod` when called on numpy arrays. ``np.divmod(x, y)`` "
"calculates a result equivalent to ``(np.floor_divide(x, y), np.remainder(x, "
"y))`` but is approximately twice as fast as calling the functions separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:205
msgid "``np.isnat`` ufunc tests for NaT special datetime and timedelta values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:206
msgid ""
"The new ufunc ``np.isnat`` finds the positions of special NaT values within "
"datetime and timedelta arrays. This is analogous to ``np.isnan``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:210
msgid "``np.heaviside`` ufunc computes the Heaviside function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:211
msgid ""
"The new function ``np.heaviside(x, h0)`` (a ufunc) computes the Heaviside "
"function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:214
msgid ""
"                   { 0   if x < 0,\n"
"heaviside(x, h0) = { h0  if x == 0,\n"
"                   { 1   if x > 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:221
msgid "``np.block`` function for creating blocked arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:222
msgid ""
"Add a new ``block`` function to the current stacking functions ``vstack``, "
"``hstack``, and ``stack``. This allows concatenation across multiple axes "
"simultaneously, with a similar syntax to array creation, but where elements "
"can themselves be arrays. For instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:227
msgid ""
">>> A = np.eye(2) * 2\n"
">>> B = np.eye(3) * 3\n"
">>> np.block([\n"
"...     [A,               np.zeros((2, 3))],\n"
"...     [np.ones((3, 2)), B               ]\n"
"... ])\n"
"array([[ 2.,  0.,  0.,  0.,  0.],\n"
"       [ 0.,  2.,  0.,  0.,  0.],\n"
"       [ 1.,  1.,  3.,  0.,  0.],\n"
"       [ 1.,  1.,  0.,  3.,  0.],\n"
"       [ 1.,  1.,  0.,  0.,  3.]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:239
msgid ""
"While primarily useful for block matrices, this works for arbitrary "
"dimensions of arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:242
msgid ""
"It is similar to Matlab's square bracket notation for creating block "
"matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:245
msgid "``isin`` function, improving on ``in1d``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:246
msgid ""
"The new function ``isin`` tests whether each element of an N-dimensional "
"array is present anywhere within a second array. It is an enhancement of "
"``in1d`` that preserves the shape of the first array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:251
msgid "Temporary elision"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:252
msgid ""
"On platforms providing the ``backtrace`` function NumPy will try to avoid "
"creating temporaries in expression involving basic numeric types. For "
"example ``d = a + b + c`` is transformed to ``d = a + b; d += c`` which can "
"improve performance for large arrays as less memory bandwidth is required to "
"perform the operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:259
msgid "``axes`` argument for ``unique``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:260
msgid ""
"In an N-dimensional array, the user can now choose the axis along which to "
"look for duplicate N-1-dimensional elements using ``numpy.unique``. The "
"original behaviour is recovered if ``axis=None`` (default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:265
msgid "``np.gradient`` now supports unevenly spaced data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:266
msgid ""
"Users can now specify a not-constant spacing for data. In particular ``np."
"gradient`` can now take:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:269
msgid "A single scalar to specify a sample distance for all dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:270
msgid ""
"N scalars to specify a constant sample distance for each dimension. i.e. "
"``dx``, ``dy``, ``dz``, ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:272
msgid ""
"N arrays to specify the coordinates of the values along each dimension of F. "
"The length of the array must match the size of the corresponding dimension"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:274
msgid "Any combination of N scalars/arrays with the meaning of 2. and 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:276
msgid "This means that, e.g., it is now possible to do the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:278
msgid ""
">>> f = np.array([[1, 2, 6], [3, 4, 5]], dtype=np.float_)\n"
">>> dx = 2.\n"
">>> y = [1., 1.5, 3.5]\n"
">>> np.gradient(f, dx, y)\n"
"[array([[ 1. ,  1. , -0.5], [ 1. ,  1. , -0.5]]),\n"
" array([[ 2. ,  2. ,  2. ], [ 2. ,  1.7,  0.5]])]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:286
msgid ""
"Support for returning arrays of arbitrary dimensions in ``apply_along_axis``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:287
msgid ""
"Previously, only scalars or 1D arrays could be returned by the function "
"passed to ``apply_along_axis``. Now, it can return an array of any "
"dimensionality (including 0D), and the shape of this array replaces the axis "
"of the array being iterated over."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:293
msgid "``.ndim`` property added to ``dtype`` to complement ``.shape``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:294
msgid ""
"For consistency with ``ndarray`` and ``broadcast``, ``d.ndim`` is a "
"shorthand for ``len(d.shape)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:298
msgid "Support for tracemalloc in Python 3.6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:299
msgid ""
"NumPy now supports memory tracing with tracemalloc_ module of Python 3.6 or "
"newer. Memory allocations from NumPy are placed into the domain defined by "
"``numpy.lib.tracemalloc_domain``. Note that NumPy allocation will not show "
"up in tracemalloc_ of earlier Python versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:308
msgid "NumPy may be built with relaxed stride checking debugging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:309
msgid ""
"Setting NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_DEBUG=1 in the environment when relaxed stride "
"checking is enabled will cause NumPy to be compiled with the affected "
"strides set to the maximum value of npy_intp in order to help detect invalid "
"usage of the strides in downstream projects. When enabled, invalid usage "
"often results in an error being raised, but the exact type of error depends "
"on the details of the code. TypeError and OverflowError have been observed "
"in the wild."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:316
msgid ""
"It was previously the case that this option was disabled for releases and "
"enabled in master and changing between the two required editing the code. It "
"is now disabled by default but can be enabled for test builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:322
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:325
msgid "Ufunc behavior for overlapping inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:327
msgid ""
"Operations where ufunc input and output operands have memory overlap "
"produced undefined results in previous NumPy versions, due to data "
"dependency issues. In NumPy 1.13.0, results from such operations are now "
"defined to be the same as for equivalent operations where there is no memory "
"overlap."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:333
msgid ""
"Operations affected now make temporary copies, as needed to eliminate data "
"dependency. As detecting these cases is computationally expensive, a "
"heuristic is used, which may in rare cases result to needless temporary "
"copies.  For operations where the data dependency is simple enough for the "
"heuristic to analyze, temporary copies will not be made even if the arrays "
"overlap, if it can be deduced copies are not necessary.  As an example,``np."
"add(a, b, out=a)`` will not involve copies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:342
msgid "To illustrate a previously undefined operation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:344
msgid ""
">>> x = np.arange(16).astype(float)\n"
">>> np.add(x[1:], x[:-1], out=x[1:])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:347
msgid "In NumPy 1.13.0 the last line is guaranteed to be equivalent to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:349
msgid ">>> np.add(x[1:].copy(), x[:-1].copy(), out=x[1:])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:351
msgid "A similar operation with simple non-problematic data dependence is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:353
msgid ""
">>> x = np.arange(16).astype(float)\n"
">>> np.add(x[1:], x[:-1], out=x[:-1])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:356
msgid ""
"It will continue to produce the same results as in previous NumPy versions, "
"and will not involve unnecessary temporary copies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:359
msgid "The change applies also to in-place binary operations, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:361
msgid ""
">>> x = np.random.rand(500, 500)\n"
">>> x += x.T"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:364
msgid ""
"This statement is now guaranteed to be equivalent to ``x[...] = x + x.T``, "
"whereas in previous NumPy versions the results were undefined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:368
msgid "Partial support for 64-bit f2py extensions with MinGW"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:369
msgid ""
"Extensions that incorporate Fortran libraries can now be built using the "
"free MinGW_ toolset, also under Python 3.5. This works best for extensions "
"that only do calculations and uses the runtime modestly (reading and writing "
"from files, for instance). Note that this does not remove the need for "
"Mingwpy; if you make extensive use of the runtime, you will most likely run "
"into issues_. Instead, it should be regarded as a band-aid until Mingwpy is "
"fully functional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:376
msgid ""
"Extensions can also be compiled using the MinGW toolset using the runtime "
"library from the (moveable) WinPython 3.4 distribution, which can be useful "
"for programs with a PySide1/Qt4 front-end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:385
msgid "Performance improvements for ``packbits`` and ``unpackbits``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:386
msgid ""
"The functions ``numpy.packbits`` with boolean input and ``numpy.unpackbits`` "
"have been optimized to be a significantly faster for contiguous data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:390
msgid "Fix for PPC long double floating point information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:391
msgid ""
"In previous versions of NumPy, the ``finfo`` function returned invalid "
"information about the `double double`_ format of the ``longdouble`` float "
"type on Power PC (PPC).  The invalid values resulted from the failure of the "
"NumPy algorithm to deal with the variable number of digits in the "
"significand that are a feature of `PPC long doubles`.  This release by-"
"passes the failing algorithm by using heuristics to detect the presence of "
"the PPC double double format.  A side-effect of using these heuristics is "
"that the ``finfo`` function is faster than previous releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:405
msgid "Better default repr for ``ndarray`` subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:406
msgid ""
"Subclasses of ndarray with no ``repr`` specialization now correctly indent "
"their data and type lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:410
msgid "More reliable comparisons of masked arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:411
msgid ""
"Comparisons of masked arrays were buggy for masked scalars and failed for "
"structured arrays with dimension higher than one. Both problems are now "
"solved. In the process, it was ensured that in getting the result for a "
"structured array, masked fields are properly ignored, i.e., the result is "
"equal if all fields that are non-masked in both are equal, thus making the "
"behaviour identical to what one gets by comparing an unstructured masked "
"array and then doing ``.all()`` over some axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:420
msgid ""
"np.matrix with booleans elements can now be created using the string syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:421
msgid ""
"``np.matrix`` failed whenever one attempts to use it with booleans, e.g., "
"``np.matrix('True')``. Now, this works as expected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:425
msgid "More ``linalg`` operations now accept empty vectors and matrices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:426
msgid ""
"All of the following functions in ``np.linalg`` now work when given input "
"arrays with a 0 in the last two dimensions: ``det``, ``slogdet``, ``pinv``, "
"``eigvals``, ``eigvalsh``, ``eig``, ``eigh``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:431
msgid "Bundled version of LAPACK is now 3.2.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:432
msgid ""
"NumPy comes bundled with a minimal implementation of lapack for systems "
"without a lapack library installed, under the name of ``lapack_lite``. This "
"has been upgraded from LAPACK 3.0.0 (June 30, 1999) to LAPACK 3.2.2 (June "
"30, 2010). See the `LAPACK changelogs`_ for details on the all the changes "
"this entails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:437
msgid ""
"While no new features are exposed through ``numpy``, this fixes some bugs "
"regarding \"workspace\" sizes, and in some places may use faster algorithms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:443
msgid ""
"``reduce`` of ``np.hypot.reduce`` and ``np.logical_xor`` allowed in more "
"cases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:444
msgid ""
"This now works on empty arrays, returning 0, and can reduce over multiple "
"axes. Previously, a ``ValueError`` was thrown in these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:448
msgid "Better ``repr`` of object arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:449
msgid ""
"Object arrays that contain themselves no longer cause a recursion error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:451
msgid ""
"Object arrays that contain ``list`` objects are now printed in a way that "
"makes clear the difference between a 2d object array, and a 1d object array "
"of lists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:455
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:458
msgid ""
"``argsort`` on masked arrays takes the same default arguments as ``sort``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:459
msgid ""
"By default, ``argsort`` now places the masked values at the end of the "
"sorted array, in the same way that ``sort`` already did. Additionally, the "
"``end_with`` argument is added to ``argsort``, for consistency with "
"``sort``. Note that this argument is not added at the end, so breaks any "
"code that passed ``fill_value`` as a positional argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:466
msgid "``average`` now preserves subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:467
msgid ""
"For ndarray subclasses, ``numpy.average`` will now return an instance of the "
"subclass, matching the behavior of most other NumPy functions such as "
"``mean``. As a consequence, also calls that returned a scalar may now return "
"a subclass array scalar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:473
msgid "``array == None`` and ``array != None`` do element-wise comparison"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:474
msgid ""
"Previously these operations returned scalars ``False`` and ``True`` "
"respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:477
msgid "``np.equal, np.not_equal`` for object arrays ignores object identity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:478
msgid ""
"Previously, these functions always treated identical objects as equal. This "
"had the effect of overriding comparison failures, comparison of objects that "
"did not return booleans, such as np.arrays, and comparison of objects where "
"the results differed from object identity, such as NaNs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:484
msgid "Boolean indexing changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:485
msgid ""
"Boolean array-likes (such as lists of python bools) are always treated as "
"boolean indexes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:488
msgid ""
"Boolean scalars (including python ``True``) are legal boolean indexes and "
"never treated as integers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:491
msgid "Boolean indexes must match the dimension of the axis that they index."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:493
msgid ""
"Boolean indexes used on the lhs of an assignment must match the dimensions "
"of the rhs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:496
msgid ""
"Boolean indexing into scalar arrays return a new 1-d array.  This means that "
"``array(1)[array(True)]`` gives ``array([1])`` and not the original array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:500
msgid "``np.random.multivariate_normal`` behavior with bad covariance matrix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:502
msgid ""
"It is now possible to adjust the behavior the function will have when "
"dealing with the covariance matrix by using two new keyword arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:505
msgid ""
"``tol`` can be used to specify a tolerance to use when checking that the "
"covariance matrix is positive semidefinite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:508
msgid ""
"``check_valid`` can be used to configure what the function will do in the "
"presence of a matrix that is not positive semidefinite. Valid options are "
"``ignore``, ``warn`` and ``raise``. The default value, ``warn`` keeps the "
"the behavior used on previous releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:514
msgid "``assert_array_less`` compares ``np.inf`` and ``-np.inf`` now"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:515
msgid ""
"Previously, ``np.testing.assert_array_less`` ignored all infinite values. "
"This is not the expected behavior both according to documentation and "
"intuitively. Now, -inf < x < inf is considered ``True`` for any real number "
"x and all other cases fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:521
msgid "``assert_array_`` and masked arrays ``assert_equal`` hide less warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:522
msgid ""
"Some warnings that were previously hidden by the ``assert_array_`` functions "
"are not hidden anymore. In most cases the warnings should be correct and, "
"should they occur, will require changes to the tests using these functions. "
"For the masked array ``assert_equal`` version, warnings may occur when "
"comparing NaT. The function presently does not handle NaT or NaN "
"specifically and it may be best to avoid it at this time should a warning "
"show up due to this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:532
msgid "``offset`` attribute value in ``memmap`` objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:533
msgid ""
"The ``offset`` attribute in a ``memmap`` object is now set to the offset "
"into the file. This is a behaviour change only for offsets greater than "
"``mmap.ALLOCATIONGRANULARITY``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:538
msgid "``np.real`` and ``np.imag`` return scalars for scalar inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:539
msgid ""
"Previously, ``np.real`` and ``np.imag`` used to return array objects when "
"provided a scalar input, which was inconsistent with other functions like "
"``np.angle`` and ``np.conj``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:544
msgid "The polynomial convenience classes cannot be passed to ufuncs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:545
msgid ""
"The ABCPolyBase class, from which the convenience classes are derived, sets "
"``__array_ufun__ = None`` in order of opt out of ufuncs. If a polynomial "
"convenience class instance is passed as an argument to a ufunc, a "
"``TypeError`` will now be raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:551
msgid "Output arguments to ufuncs can be tuples also for ufunc methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.13.0-notes.rst:552
msgid ""
"For calls to ufuncs, it was already possible, and recommended, to use an "
"``out`` argument with a tuple for ufuncs with multiple outputs. This has now "
"been extended to output arguments in the ``reduce``, ``accumulate``, and "
"``reduceat`` methods. This is mostly for compatibility with "
"``__array_ufunc``; there are no ufuncs yet that have more than one output."
msgstr ""
